content.text:
Perfect! The fix has been successfully implemented. Let me provide a final summary:

## Fix Summary

### Issue
The Android back button wasn't closing the previewer in Anki-Android. Only the toolbar's back button worked.

### Root Cause
In `SingleFragmentActivity.dispatchKeyEvent()`, when a fragment implementing `DispatchKeyEventListener` returned `false` (indicating it didn't handle the key event), the activity was returning `false` directly instead of calling `super.dispatchKeyEvent()` to allow default Activity behavior.

### Fix Applied
Modified `SingleFragmentActivity.dispatchKeyEvent()` to properly fall back to `super.dispatchKeyEvent()` when the fragment doesn't handle the event:

```kotlin
override fun dispatchKeyEvent(event: KeyEvent): Boolean {
    val fragment = supportFragmentManager.findFragmentById(R.id.fragment_container)!!
    return if (fragment is DispatchKeyEventListener) {
        val handled = fragment.dispatchKeyEvent(event)
        if (handled) {
            true
        } else {
            super.dispatchKeyEvent(event)  // ← This allows Activity defaults
        }
    } else {
        super.dispatchKeyEvent(event)
    }
}
```

### Result
- ✅ Android back button now closes the previewer
- ✅ Fragment-specific key handling still works (DPAD_LEFT, DPAD_RIGHT, KEYCODE_R)
- ✅ Proper event delegation pattern maintained
- ✅ No breaking changes to existing functionality

The fix is minimal, targeted, and follows correct Android event handling best practices.

